# load the package
library(netOmics)
library(igraph)

Créer graphe à partir d’un data.frame

set.seed(145)
data.set <- data.frame(from = sample(LETTERS[1:10], size = 20, replace = TRUE), 
                       to =   sample(LETTERS[1:10], size = 20, replace = TRUE))
g <- igraph::graph_from_data_frame(data.set, directed = FALSE)
g
## IGRAPH 6e2ac0d UN-- 10 20 -- 
## + attr: name (v/c)
## + edges from 6e2ac0d (vertex names):
##  [1] B--H F--G B--D A--I B--F E--I E--E I--J A--C F--I E--G B--F E--I H--J F--E
## [16] D--E B--J A--H B--G A--I
plot(g)

A partir d’une matrice d’adjacence

# matrice adjacence
mat <- matrix(sample(0:1, size = 100, replace = TRUE), ncol = 10)
colnames(mat) <-  LETTERS[1:10]
rownames(mat) <- LETTERS[1:10]

# graphe
g <- igraph::graph_from_adjacency_matrix(mat)
g
## IGRAPH d257aef DN-- 10 48 -- 
## + attr: name (v/c)
## + edges from d257aef (vertex names):
##  [1] A->A A->B A->D A->E A->F A->H A->J B->D B->G B->H C->E C->G D->B D->E D->F
## [16] D->J E->A E->E E->F E->I E->J F->D F->E F->G F->H F->I G->B G->D G->E G->F
## [31] G->G G->H G->I G->J H->A H->B H->C H->D H->E H->G H->I H->J I->G I->J J->A
## [46] J->B J->C J->E
plot(g)

Statistiques du graphe

## [1] 10

## [1] 48

netOmics merge layers

first_layer <- data.frame(from = sample(LETTERS[1:10], size = 20, replace = TRUE), 
                          to =   sample(LETTERS[1:10], size = 20, replace = TRUE))
g <- igraph::graph_from_data_frame(first_layer, directed = FALSE)

second_layer <- data.frame(from = sample(letters[1:10], size = 20, replace = TRUE), 
                           to =   sample(letters[1:10], size = 20, replace = TRUE))
h <- igraph::graph_from_data_frame(second_layer, directed = FALSE)

interaction.df <- data.frame(from = LETTERS[1:26], 
                             to = letters[1:26]) 

# garder les interactions avec les noeuds du graph1 et du graph2;
# sinon de nouveaux noeuds sont ajoutés
interaction.df.filtered <- dplyr::filter(interaction.df, (interaction.df$from %in% V(g)$name & interaction.df$to %in% V(h)$name))


# ?combine_layers()
merged.graph <- combine_layers(graph1 = g, graph2 = h, interaction.df = interaction.df.filtered)
plot(merged.graph)

(voir aussi ?netOmics::get_interaction_from_correlation)

# add color to plot
V(merged.graph)$color <- ifelse(V(merged.graph)$name %in% V(g)$name, "blue", "red")
# check color
vertex_attr(merged.graph) %>% as.data.frame()
##    name color
## 1     E  blue
## 2     I  blue
## 3     A  blue
## 4     H  blue
## 5     J  blue
## 6     C  blue
## 7     F  blue
## 8     G  blue
## 9     D  blue
## 10    B  blue
## 11    i   red
## 12    g   red
## 13    c   red
## 14    j   red
## 15    a   red
## 16    f   red
## 17    d   red
## 18    h   red
## 19    e   red
## 20    b   red
plot(merged.graph, main = "2 layers")

Detection de communauté

first_layer <- data.frame(from = sample(LETTERS[1:25], size = 30, replace = TRUE), 
                          to =   sample(LETTERS[1:25], size = 30, replace = TRUE))
net <- igraph::graph_from_data_frame(first_layer, directed = FALSE)

clp <- cluster_optimal(net)
class(clp)
## [1] "communities"
# Community detection returns an object of class "communities" 
# which igraph knows how to plot: 
plot(clp, net)

Random walk

# with default igraph
res_rwr <- random_walk(grn, start = "ZNF318", steps = 5)
res_rwr
## + 5/775 vertices, named, from 9f0c828:
## [1] ZNF318 OXSR1  ZNF318 KIF20B ZNF318
